Variable Description

customer_ID - A unique identifier for the customer

shopping_pt - Unique identifier for the shopping point of a given customer

record_type - 0=shopping point, 1=purchase point

day - Day of the week (0-6, 0=Monday)

time - Time of day (HH:MM)

state - State where shopping point occurred

location - Location ID where shopping point occurred

group_size - How many people will be covered under the policy (1, 2, 3 or 4)

homeowner - Whether the customer owns a home or not (0=no, 1=yes)

car_age - Age of the customers car

car_value - How valuable was the customers car when new

risk_factor - An ordinal assessment of how risky the customer is (1, 2, 3, 4)

age_oldest - Age of the oldest person in customers group

age_youngest - Age of the youngest person in customers group

married_couple - Does the customer group contain a married couple (0=no, 1=yes)

C_previous - What the customer formerly had or currently has for product option C (0=nothing, 1, 2, 3,4)

duration_previous - how long (in years) the customer was covered by their previous issuer

A,B,C,D,E,F,G - the coverage options

cost - cost of the quoted coverage options

Train, Valid, Test

Created the train, test, and valid sets. I broke them up by customer ID because there is not pattern in customer ID and cost so this is essentially the same thing as breaking them up randomly. I then took all of the column with record type 1 from the valid set and made it the test set because I am trying to predict the the cost of what customers will buy based on previous customers and the quotes that the customers have already been given.

allstate$train_id <- 1
allstate$train_id[allstate$customer_ID < 10004681]="Train"
allstate$train_id[allstate$customer_ID >= 10004681]="Valid"
allstate$train_id[allstate$train_id == "Valid" & allstate$record_type == 1]="Test"

Single Variable for Type of Plan

I made a single variable for the type of plan as given by the variables A-G. I did this by combining the numbers given from A-G and making a sort of id code for each plan. Then I used a code the give a number starting with for each unique value of the plan code I made. I subtracted 1 from that so the plans start with 0.

allstate$plan <- as.numeric(paste(allstate$A, allstate$B, allstate$C, allstate$D, allstate$E, allstate$F, allstate$G, sep = ""))

allstate$plan <- sprintf("%07d",allstate$plan)

allstate <- transform(allstate,id=as.numeric(factor(allstate$plan)))

allstate$id <- allstate$id - 1

New Variables

I created a continuous variable for time. Since there were no values for some of the variables I replaced them with 0.

allstate$time <- as.numeric(as.POSIXct(allstate$time))

allstate$risk_factor[is.na(allstate$risk_factor)] <- 0
allstate$C_previous[is.na(allstate$C_previous)] <- 0
allstate$duration_previous[is.na(allstate$duration_previous)] <- 0

allstate <- left_join(allstate, group, by = "customer_ID")

Nearest Neighbors to Predict Plan

I used nearest neighbors to predict what plan the customers I am testing on would buy since I do not know that. Certain plans will most likely cost more than others so it is important to have the plan for predicting cost.

library(FNN)


X <- as.matrix(select(allstate, customer_ID))
y <- allstate$id
X_train <- X[allstate$train_id == "Train" | allstate$train_id =="Valid",]
y_train <- y[allstate$train_id == "Train" | allstate$train_id =="Valid"]

allstate$id_pred <- knn(train = X_train, test = X,
                     cl = y_train, k = 3)

It gives me around a 67% to 70% accuracy for the train and valid sets and judging by looking at the values from the train set that have a record type of 1 it should predict around the same for my test set.

tapply(allstate$id_pred == allstate$id, allstate$train_id, mean)
##      Test     Train     Valid 
##        NA 0.6715274 0.6962425

Next I made a new variable called id1 that takes all the plans from the ones I know, so the train and valid set, but then uses the predictions from above for the test set.

allstate$dummy <- 0
allstate$dummy[allstate$train_id == "Test"] <- 1

allstate$id[allstate$train_id == "Test"] <- 0

allstate$id1 <- as.numeric(as.character(allstate$id_pred)) * allstate$dummy + allstate$id

allstate$id[allstate$train_id == "Test"]=NA

Glmnet

I used Glmnet to determine which variables were significant in predicting the cost. It turns out that whether the person is a homeowner, the age of the car, the age of the youngest person on the plan, whether they are a married couple or not, c previous, duration previous, and the dummies for Delaware, Iowa, Indiana, Rhode Island, and DC are significant.

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loaded glmnet 2.0-13
X <- as.matrix(allstate[,c("customer_ID", "shopping_pt", "record_type", "day", "time", "location", "group_size", "homeowner", "car_age", "risk_factor", "age_oldest", "age_youngest", "married_couple", "C_previous", "duration_previous", "DE", "IA", "Indiana", "RI", "DC", "SD")])
y <- allstate$cost

X_train <- X[allstate$train_id == "Train",]
y_train <- y[allstate$train_id == "Train"]
X_valid <- X[allstate$train_id == "Test",]
y_valid <- y[allstate$train_id == "Test"]

model <- cv.glmnet(X_train, y_train, alpha = .9)

GAM Model

I put all the variable that were shown to be significant into the gam model as well as the mean cost and plan id with the predicted values from the knn model. It had a fairly good RMSE for both train and valid and did not appear to be too overfit.

library(gam)
## Loading required package: splines
## Loaded gam 1.14-4
model <- gam(cost ~ homeowner + DE + IA + Indiana + RI + DC + s(car_age) + s(age_youngest) + married_couple + s(C_previous) + s(duration_previous) + s(id1) + s(cost_mean), subset = train_id == "Train",data = allstate)

allstate$gam_pred <- predict(model, newdata = allstate)


sqrt(tapply((allstate$cost - allstate$gam_pred)^2,
            allstate$train_id, mean))
##     Test    Train    Valid 
##       NA 15.82522 15.11317

I checked to see how accurate is was on the Test set by comparing it with the Test Answers data set I had made earlier. The RMSE was around less than $18

Test_Preds <- filter(allstate, allstate$train_id == "Test")
Test_Preds <- select(Test_Preds, customer_ID, gam_pred)
Test_Answers <- left_join(Test_Answers, Test_Preds, by = "customer_ID")
sqrt(tapply((Test_Answers$cost - Test_Answers$gam_pred)^2,
            Test_Answers$train_id, mean))
##     Test 
## 17.61618

Gradient Boosted Tree Model

I used the same variables are in the gam model but in a gradient boosted tree model. It turned out to have very good RMSEs on the test and valid sets.

library(xgboost)
## 
## Attaching package: 'xgboost'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     slice
X <- model.matrix(~ .-1, data=allstate[,c("customer_ID", "shopping_pt", "record_type", "location", "group_size", "homeowner", "car_age", "risk_factor", "age_oldest", "age_youngest", "married_couple", "C_previous", "duration_previous", "cost_mean", "id1", "DE", "IA", "Indiana", "RI", "DC")])
y <- allstate$cost
X_train <- X[allstate$train_id == "Train",]
y_train <- y[allstate$train_id == "Train"]
X_valid <- X[allstate$train_id == "Valid",]
y_valid <- y[allstate$train_id == "Valid"]

data_train <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X_train, label = y_train)
data_valid <- xgb.DMatrix(data = X_valid, label = y_valid)
watchlist <- list(train=data_train, valid=data_valid)

model <- xgb.train(data = data_train,
                 max_depth = 4, eta = 0.01, nthread = 4,
                 nrounds = 5000, objective = "reg:linear",
                 watchlist = watchlist,
                 print_every_n = 1000)

Nearest Neighbors Model

The last model I tried was a k nearest neighbors model. I used a k of 3 and only customer ID as the matching variable because I wanted to compare it to the previous quotes that the customer asked for previously.

X <- as.matrix(select(allstate, customer_ID))
y <- allstate$cost
X_train <- X[allstate$train_id == "Train" | allstate$train_id =="Valid",]
y_train <- y[allstate$train_id == "Train" | allstate$train_id =="Valid"]

allstate$knn_pred <- knn(train = X_train, test = X,
                     cl = y_train, k = 3)

allstate$knn_pred <- as.numeric(as.character(allstate$knn_pred))

sqrt(tapply((allstate$cost - allstate$knn_pred)^2,
            allstate$train_id, mean))
##     Test    Train    Valid 
##       NA 22.13998 20.89674

This gave me the best RMSE out of any of the models with it being about $17.31

Blended Model

Finally I blended the model. This decreased RMSE only slightly from before.

model <- lm(cost ~ xgb_pred + gam_pred + knn_pred,
            data = allstate,
            subset = (train_id == "Valid"))

Conclusion

I would either choose the blended model or the gam model if I were predicting new customers. While the knn model has the lowest individual RMSE it is solely basing it off of previously looked at quotes from the customer so if the customer changed more drastically for their final purchase then it would not be able to predict accurately. Whereas the GAM model takes into account more factors so it can better adapt to odd values if a customer is doing more abnormal shopping.
